    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-10-14T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-10-14T20:00:00-05:00" n="428"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d428">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.90H/37: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Straus</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-10-14T20:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 14, 1935—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>425. Your 863, October 7, 6.00 p.m. As stated in Department’s 209, June 5, 5.00
                    p.m., it is the policy of this Government to conclude commercial agreements
                    providing for most-favored-nation treatment. Unless this principle is concurred
                    in by Afghanistan, the Department would not feel in a position to recommend
                    acceptance of the agreement. Provided unconditional most-favored-nation
                    treatment is assured, Department is not greatly concerned about the form or
                    language of the provision. It would seem to be possible to omit the words
                    “immediately and unconditionally” and still achieve the result.</p>
                <p>If the Afghan Minister understands this and accepts fully the principle of
                    unconditional most-favored-nation treatment, Department will be glad to submit
                    new language calculated to accomplish this purpose.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
